<SubSection title="Classical mechanics" id="classical_mechanics">

    <CalloutContainer slot="cards">
        <CalloutCard>
            <p>
                If we have objects which are either very massive, very
                small, or moving very fast, then Newton's equations do not
                provide a good model of their motion. Instead we must use
                Einstein's equations of <a
                target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_relativity">general
                relativity</a> (for massive and fast objects) or the
                equations of <a
                target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics">quantum
                mechanics</a> (for very small objects). Unfortunately,
                these two theories cannot be used together, so we
                currently have no good models for objects which are
                simultaneously very small and very massive, such as <a
                target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micro_black_hole">micro
                black holes</a> or the universe shortly after the <a
                target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Bang">big
                bang</a>. Physicists are currently trying to reconcile
                general relativity with quantum mechanics by devising a
                new set of equations (sometimes called <a
                target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_gravity">quantum
                gravity</a> or a <a
                target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theory_of_everything">theory
                of everything</a>). Current possibilities for new
                equations include <a
                target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/String_theory">string
                theory</a> and <a
                target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loop_quantum_gravity">loop
                quantum gravity</a>, but none of these are generally
                accepted yet.
              </p>
              <p>
                It is important to remember that all of these different
                equations are only models of reality and are not actually
                real:
              </p>
              <blockquote>
                “All models are wrong. Some models are useful.”
                <br />
                — <a target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_E._P._Box">George Box</a>
              </blockquote>
        </CalloutCard>
    </CalloutContainer>

    Newton's equations relate the acceleration <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{a}" /> of a point mass with mass <InlineEquation equation="m" /> to the total applied force <InlineEquation equation="\\vec{F}" /> on the mass (sum of all applied forces). They are:
    
    <DisplayEquation equation="\\vec{F} = m\\vec{a}" background="True" title="Newton's equations: "/>

    There is no derivation for Newton's equations, because they are an assumed model for dynamics. We can only verify them by comparing with experimental evidence, which confirms that Newtonian dynamics are accurate for non-relativistic and non-quantum systems.

